'''Alan Coren''' (27 June 1938{{cn|date=March 2011}} &ndash; 18 October 2007){{cn|date=March 2011}} was an [[English people|English]] [[List of humorists|humorist]], [[writer]] and [[satire|satirist]] who was well known as a regular panellist on the [[BBC]] [[radio]] [[quiz]] ''[[The News Quiz]]'' and a team captain on BBC television's ''[[Call My Bluff (UK game show)|Call My Bluff]]''. Coren was also a journalist, and for nine years was the editor of ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'' magazine.

==Early life==
{{unsourced section|date=March 2011}}
Alan Coren was born in [[Southgate]], north [[London]] in 1938, the son of a [[Construction worker|builder]] and a hairdresser.

==Education==
Coren was educated at [[East Grinstead Grammar School]], followed by [[Wadham College, Oxford|Wadham College]] at the [[University of Oxford]] to which he gained a scholarship, and where he got a [[British undergraduate degree classification|First]] in [[English language|English]] in 1960. After taking a [[Master's degree]]<ref name="Tele Obit">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=&xml=/news/2007/10/20/db2001.xml|title=Obituary - Alan Coren|first=|last=|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 October 2007}}</ref><ref name="BBC Obit">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7052749.stm|title=Obituary: Alan Coren|first=|last=|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=19 October 2007}}</ref> he studied for a [[doctorate]] in [[American literature|modern American literature]] at [[Yale University|Yale]] and the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name="Tele Obit"/>

==Life and career==
Coren considered an [[Academia|academic]] career but decided instead to become a writer and journalist.<ref name="Times Obit">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article2696826.ece?token=null&offset=0|title=Obituary - Alan Coren|first=|last=|publisher=[[The Times]]|date=20 October 2007 | location=London}}</ref> He began this career by selling articles to ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'' and was later offered a full-time job there.<ref name="BBC Obit"/> At this time he also wrote for ''[[The New Yorker]]''.<ref name="Tele Obit"/> 

In 1966, he became ''Punch'''s literary editor, and went on to become deputy editor in 1969 and editor in 1978. He remained as editor until 1987 when the circulation began to decline.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news|url=http://media.guardian.co.uk/presspublishing/comment/0,,2195300,00.html|title=Obituary - Alan Coren|first=Stanley|last=Reynolds|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 October 2007}}</ref> Unsurprisingly, during the week in which he took over the editorship, the ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'' published a profile of him. His response was to rush around the office, waving a copy of the relevant edition, saying: "This is ridiculous - I haven't been Jewish for years!"<ref name="Indie">{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article3078970.ece|title=Obituary - Alan Coren|first=Miles|last=Kington|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=20 October 2007}}</ref>

From 1971 to 1978, Coren wrote a television review column for ''The Times'' and a humour column for the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' from 1972 to 1976.<ref name="Times Obit"/> Succeeding [[John Cleese]], in 1973 Coren became the [[Rector of the University of St Andrews]] in [[St Andrews]] in [[Fife]] on the East coast of Scotland, and remained so until 1976.<ref name="Tele Obit"/>

When he left ''Punch'' in 1987, he became editor of ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]'', continuing in that role until 1989.<ref name="Tele Obit"/> From 1984 Coren worked as a television critic for the ''[[Daily Mail|Mail on Sunday]]'' until he moved as a humorous columnist to the ''[[Daily Express|Sunday Express]]'', which he left in 1996.<ref name="Tele Obit"/><ref name="Guardian"/> Known as the "Sage of [[Cricklewood]]", where he lived, his columns always contained humour and criticism. From 1975 to 1982 Coren wrote comic essays, such as ''Golfing for Cats'' and ''The Cricklewood Diet'' and from 1976 to 1983 wrote the ''Arthur'' series of children's books.<ref name="Tele Obit"/> In 1989 he started a column in ''[[The Times]]'', which he continued for the rest of his life.<ref name="BBC"/>

In 1977, while writing for ''[[The Observer]]'', ''[[Tatler]]'' and ''The Times'', Alan Coren began his broadcasting career when he became one of the regular panellists on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s new [[Satire|satirical]] quiz show, ''[[The News Quiz]]''.<ref name="BBC Obit"/> In 1978 he wrote ''[[The Losers (TV series)|The Losers]]'', an unsuccessful [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] about a [[wrestling]] [[Promoter (entertainment)|promoter]] starring [[Leonard Rossiter]] and [[Alfred Molina]].<ref name="Times Obit"/> He continued on ''The News Quiz'' until the year of his death. From 1996 to 2005 he was also one of two team captains on television's ''[[Call My Bluff (UK game show)|Call My Bluff]]''. 

During his life he wrote nearly 20 books, many of which were collections of his newspaper columns.<ref name="Tele Obit"/> One of Coren's most successful, ''The Collected Bulletins of Idi Amin'', a collection of his ''Punch'' articles about [[Idi Amin|Amin]], was rejected for publication in the [[United States]] on the grounds of racial sensitivity.<ref name="Tele Obit" /><ref name="BBC Obit" /> These Bulletins were later made into a comedy album, ''[[The Collected Broadcasts of Idi Amin]]'' with [[John Bird (actor)|John Bird]]. His other books include ''The Dog It Was That Died'' (1965), ''The Sanity Inspector'' (1974), ''All Except The Bastard'' (1978), ''The Lady from Stalingrad Mansions'' (1978), ''Rhinestone as Big as the Ritz'' (1979), ''Tissues for Men'' (1981), ''Bumf'' (1984), ''Seems Like Old Times: a Year in the Life of Alan Coren'' (1989), ''More Like Old Times'' (1990), ''A Year in Cricklewood'' (1991), ''Toujours Cricklewood?'' (1993), ''Alan Coren's Sunday Best'' (1993), ''A Bit on the Side'' (1995), ''Alan Coren Omnibus'' (1996), ''The Cricklewood Dome'' (1998), ''The Cricklewood Tapestry'' (2002) and ''Waiting for Jeffrey'' (2002).<ref name="Times Obit"/><ref name="Tele Obit"/><ref name="Guardian"/> Coren's final book, ''69 For One'', was published late in 2007.<ref name="Tele Obit"/>

==Later years==
In May 2006, Coren was bitten by an [[insect]] that gave him [[Sepsis|septicaemia]] which led to his developing [[Necrotizing fasciitis|necrotising fasciitis]].<ref name="Tele Obit"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Notebook: Before I was so rudely interrupted|work=[[The Times]]|month=December|year=2006|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/alan_coren/article758463.ece | location=London}}</ref> 

He died from [[cancer]] in 2007 at his home in [[North London]].<ref name="Express">{{cite news|url=|title=Brilliantly funny Alan Coren dies, aged 69|first=Elisa|last=Roche|publisher=[[Daily Express]]|date=20 October 2007}}</ref><ref name="BBC">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7052510.stm|title=Broadcaster Alan Coren dies at 69|first=|last=|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=19 October 2007}}</ref> Survived by his wife Anne (''n<U+00E9>e'' Kasriel), whom he married in 1963,<ref name="Times Obit"/><ref name="Indie"/> and their two children, [[Giles Coren|Giles]] and [[Victoria Coren|Victoria]], who are both [[journalist]]s,<ref name="BBC"/> he was buried in [[Hampstead Cemetery]].<ref name="Express"/> An anthology of his writings, called ''The Essential Alan Coren - Chocolate and Cuckoo Clocks'' and edited by his children, was published on 2 October 2008.<ref name="gate">{{cite web|url=http://www.meetatthegate.com/component/option,com_author_book/edition_id,997/title_id,1196/|title=Meet at the Gate - Chocolate and Cuckoo Clocks|accessdate=2008-12-29|author=|last=|first=|year=2008|format=|work=|publisher=meetatthegate.com}}</ref>

